{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_horsetail_ver01/data/sn86075293/00340581908/1927072201/0229.xml":{"full_text":"|Jlnttyfaoob \u00eeferalb.\nPUBLISHED EVERY FRIDAY\nC. S. NELSON, Editor and Publisher.\nEntered as \u00bbecood-claa* matter Novemtar 13\n1*08 at the poat office at Plentywood Montana,\nunder the Act of March J. 187M\nTerms\u2014In Advance, per year $2.00\nAdvertising Rales, very reasonable, will\nbe furnished upon application\nThe Road Hog\nThe road hog season is here\u2014in fact\nwe are in the midst of it\u2014and one is apt\nto meet most any variety of this most\ndangerous of modern wild animals on the\nstreets or highways, especially of an eve\nning.\nWhen confronted by a road hog, two\ncourses of proceedure are open to the mo\ntorist: he can hold his half of the road\nand smash it out with the best, or give it\ngangway by taking to the fields or the\nditch as the case may be. In a majority\nof eases, it is the ditch.\nEither course, however, is nerve-rack\ning and often productive of extensive\ndamage to both car and feelings. And\nnot only are the feelings likely to be hurt,\nbut there is always the possibility of\nbreaking a few bones at inconvenient\nplaces.\nRoad hogs may be divided into two\nprincipal classes-the deliberate ones, who\nescape hanging by a vigilante committee\nonly because the vigilante days are past,\nand the unintentional ones whose actions\nare the result of fear lest thev get too\nclose to the ditch ttiemselves. This latter\nclass is generally seized by the hogging\nimpulse only when so badly blinded by\nheadlights that they cannot see to the\nside. They imagine the results of pulling\nover too far ami prefer to take chances on\nstaying in the main track. They are ev\nen more dangerous than the deliberate\nones, who will often lose their nerve in\nthe last ten feet and swing out in time to\navoid a crash.\nPublic opinion is the most effective ex\ntermiuatior of the road tiog. At times it\nis possible to rsach them by recourse to\nlegal proceedings but as a rule the only\nefficient treatment is a thorough dos-; of\npublic contempt.\nDon't Sell U. S. Short\nIt has long been a sort of axiom in\nAmerican financial circles that it doesn't\npay to sell Uncle Sam \"short.\" In these\ndays when we occassionally hear from\nthe professional gloom spreaders it is well\nto keep this truism in mind. Uncle Sara\nis not going to the bow-wows. If he is.\nthen what is going to happen to the rest\nof the world first? For the economic con\ndition of the United States is so much\nbetter off than any other country that\nthere is hardly any comparisno. So if\nUncle Sam is going to be submerged in\ndepression, which so the oessimists tell\nus, is to be world-wide, then the rest of\nthe universe is going to be in over its\nhead before the waters ge: to Uncle Sam's\nknees.\nAs a matter of fact, despite unsatis\nfactory local conditions in a few parts of\nthe country, the nation is forging steadily\nahead on the path of progress and prosj\nperitv. The Nation Association of Manu\nfacturers recently published its annual\nmidsummer survey, and this report shows\nthat there is no indication of any slnmp\nin employment in the United States for\nthe next few months at least. It is stated\nthat industries are operating on eighty\none per cent of their maximum employ\nment capacity, which is regarded as a re\nmarkable record for midsummer business.\nNinety per cent of the factories in the\ncountry, it is estimated, are now operat\ning on a high production scale.\nIn commenting on the report President\nEdgerton of the Association said: \"Ana\nlyzing the reports that have come to us\nfrom all sections of the country, I believe\nthe whole nation can be happy in the em\nployment and business outlook for 'he\nsummer and earlv fall. The situation is\nhealthy. The survey covered twenty\nthree classifications of industry: Agricul\ntural machinery, automobiles, automobile\naccessories, builders and plumbers' sup\nplies. chemicals, clothing, electrical and\nradio, food, furniture, glass, hardware\nand tools, instruments, jewelry, leather,\nlumber, machinery, music, printing, pot\ntery and clay, rubber, steel and Iron,\ntextiles and miscellaneocs.\"\nThe condition of the American producer\nis so much belter than the condition of\nthe producer in any other country of the\nworld that we ought to be more than\nthankful lor prosperity and the high stan\ndard of living which has come to us, and\nto see that nothing is done to interfere\nwith the application of the economic prin\nciples which have brought this condition\nabout.\nThe Prussian Diet's session was broken\nup the other day by a fist fight between\nnationalists and republicans. Who says\nthat Germany hasn't caught the spirit of\ndemocracy?\nRiver Really Fallt\nFall River, In Massachusetts, takes\nUs name from a river so called be\ncause It is only about two miles la\nlength and falls about 140 feet In a\nhalf-mile.\nCHURCH NOTICES\nSt. Joseph's Church\nMaas first Sun. of each month at 11 a. m.\nMass 2nd Sun. of each month at 9 a. m.\nMass third Sun. of each month at 11a. m.\nMass 4th Sun. of each month at 8:30 a.in.\nDaily mass at 8 a. m.\nEvangelical Church\nSunday School at 10:00 a. in\nPrayer meeting each Wed. at 7:30 p. m\nTWO TREE\nSunday School at 10:00 a. m\nPreaching at 1100\nAll are welcome.\nH. L. CALVERT, pastor.\nFirst Congregational\nSunday School at 10:00 A. M.\nWorship Service at 11:00 A. M\nYoung People's Service at 7.00 P. M,\nChoir Practice Thursday evenings at 7:30.\nDOOLEY\nChurch School every Wednesday, 4 p. m.\nANTELOPE\nSunday School at\nPreaching services every Sunday\nevening at 8 o'clock\nRev. Earle A. Clifford, Minister.\n10:30 A. M.\nLutheran Church\nSunday School at 10 a. m.\nNo services as the pastor will be at\nFroid to assist at the ordination and in\nstallation of the new pastor.\nThe confirmation class at Dooley will\nmeet Monday July 25 at 2 p. m.\nTwo week term of religious school will\nbe held at the Dooley Lutheran church\nbeginning Monday morning July 25 at\n9 a. m. with Miss Mate! Foss in charge.\nTrust the parents will avail themselves\nof this opportunity and send their children\nregularly. All the children of the com\nmunity are welcome.\nEverybody welcome.\nA. M. Egge, Pastor.\nAssembly of God\nServices: Sunday School at 2 p. m.\nPreaching services at 3 p. m.\nEvangelistic services at 7:30 p. m.\nWed. night prayer service at 7:30 p. m.\nServices are held in the building three\nblocks south of the Progressive Elevator.\nEvang C. R. Norman in charge.\n\nTHE MINT\nWe carry a complete line of all\nSoft Drinks, Malt. Cigars, Candy,\nTobaccos, Nut land Confectionery.\nO. M. STADIG\nPlentywood, Mont.\nPowerful Court\nIn every 4 town there Is a sort of\nsupreme court made up of the gossips;\nIt Is always In session, does not mind\nwhere It sits and from Its decision\u00ab\nthere Is no uppeaj.\u2014The Outlook.\nWONDER BOX! WONDER BOX!\nGET ONE, THEY CONTAIN\n1 6-oz. bottle Vanilla and 4-oz. bottle Lemor,\nbottle Furniture' Polish, box Soap, can Baking\nPowder, $2.30 value for $1.40.\nBottle Vanilla and Lemon value $2.25 for $1.75.\nGoods delivered for 10c extra per set.\nfor free Money Saving lists to\nSend\nALBERT L, FOLEY,\nBox 508\nCHOPS\nChops of your choice\nmoke such an appetiz\ning dish for breakfast,\ndinner or supper. Easy\nto prepare in a num\nber of different ways.\nMince Meat, Pickles, Kraut\nSend your order in early\nLamb\nPork\nVeal\nFRED FORMAN, Prop.\nPhone 17\nPLENTY WOOD MARKET\n(Corrected every Friday)\nWheat. Dark Northern.\nWheat, Winter.\nWheat, \u00c4mter Durum.\nWheat. Mixed Durum.\nFla*\nOats.'....\nRye.\nBarley.\nButter.\nEggs.\nSI 20\nus\n1.25\n1.17\n1.80\n.60\n.75\n.75\n.25\n.15\nAntelope News\nAlbert Rorvig and family returned the\nfirst of the week after making a visit to\ntheir old home in Minnesota.\nMrs. Robt Linteicum and children left\nTuesday for their home at Chadron.\nNebr.\nSeveral members of the Sons of Norwav\nlodge have teen busy the past few doys\ngetting their building ready for the ede\nbration to be held there the 22nd and\n23rd.\nFred Ibsen was a business visitor here\nfrom Plentywood Tuesday.\nMr, Packard from Plentywood was here\nWednesday on business.\nMr. and Mrs. Arthur Olson returned\nThursday from a visit at their old home\nat Fosston, Minn.\nElmer Berneau and Jens Jenson each\nreceivee a new Holt combines this week.\nGeo. Baxter, State Scale inspector, was\nhere Saturday and inspected the Grain\nElevators scales.\nIt seems strange to the writer that two\nof Plentywood's Big Political Guns who\nare always clamering about saving the\ntax paye\u00e7\u00bb money and are always laud\ning the Honor system of assessments fail\nto appear on the published tax lists for\neven a two dollar Poor or Poll tax. Some\nHonor.\nWm. Glaze and [family were up from\nCulbertson Sunday.\nPRINT SHOP CALLERS\nSO SCUD US THE 'j\nPAPER, ASAlkJ, PLEASE\nI JUST BECAUSE MV H\ng HUS9AVJD SOY MAO 0\nI? AWO ORDERED OU\u00abj\n|y Copy otscouruoueo J\n|]lS WO REASOU wnv|\n||f 1 SHOULD BE \u00abf\nDEPRIVED OF MV\nI BEST READtua (\u00dc\n\nw\n\u00cf\ni ?a\nKJ\nSWBE'\n(Beil\nOther a Trying to Learn\nSome men are born leaders and\nmost women are born drivers.\u2014Ch)\ncage Dally News.\n1\na\nQJ\nFarmers Attention!\nThe last Big rain surely put Sher\nidan County on High.\nAnd in\npreparing for the Bumper harvest\nremember we are headquarters\nfor the following essentials:\nTwine\nBinder Whips\nOils and Greases\nBelting\nNose Guards\nFly Nets\nSweat pads\nHarness\nCollars\nCopper and Tublar rivets\nKitchen utensils\nPaints\nWagon Box Bottoms\nHay rack clamps\nWagon eveners\nHay and Barley Forks\nScoop Shovels\nFly Spray\nLAST BUT USUALLY FIRST\n\nAllis Chalmer Tractors\nCase Tractors\nCase Combines\nChevrolet Trucks\nChevrolet Cars\nGet your order in now. Call now\non the largest and most Com\nplete Stock in Eastern Montana\nand have all requirements taken\ncare of. SPECIAL. A carload\nof fresh furniture about